{"title_page": "Claudia Bernadine Elisabeth Hartert", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Claudia Bernadine Elisabeth Hartert\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Claudia Endris\n| birth_date         = 21 June 1863\n| birth_place        = [[Coesfeld]], Germany\n| death_date         = 24 August 1958\n| burial_place       = \n| death_place        = [[Hilversum|Hilversum, Netherlands]]\n| othername          = \n| occupation         = Ornithologist, illustrator\n| years_active       = \n| spouse             = [[Ernst Hartert]] (m. July 1891)\n| signature          = \n| children           = Joachim Karl Hartert (1893\u20131916)\n| mother             = Alwine Florentine Sophie B\u00f6cker\n| father             = Lieutenant Colonel Joachim Endris\n| nationality        = British\n}}\n'''Claudia Bernadine Elisabeth Hartert,''' (1863 \u2013 1958) was a British/German ornithologist and illustrator. She was a British citizen born in Germany. \n\n== Biography ==\nBorn '''Claudia Endris'''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://nha.blob.core.windows.net/scans/BS%20Overlijden/Hilversum/1958/NL_HlmNHA_O_HIL_1958_0308.jpg|title=Scan of Death Certificate|last=Endris|first=Claudia Bernadine Elizabeth|date=1958|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=simpleSearch&cqlMode=true&query=nid=115349731X|title=Katalog der Deutschen Nationalbibliothek|website=portal.dnb.de|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> (or Endriss) (21 June 1863 in [[Coesfeld]], Germany),<ref name=\":1\" /> Claudia's father was Lieutenant Colonel Joachim Endris, her mother's name was Alwine Florentine Sophie, n\u00e9e B\u00f6cker.<ref name=\":1\" /> Claudia's older brother was Gustav Joachim (b. 1862). \n\nIn July 1891, Claudia married the ornithologist [[Ernst Hartert]]<ref name=\":2\" /> in [[Frankfurt|Frankfurt am Main]], Germany, with whom she had a son named son Joachim Karl Hartert, (1893\u20131916), who was killed as an English soldier during the [[Battle of the Somme]] in [[France]].<ref name=\":4\">\"Obituary: ERNST JOHANN OTTO HARTERT. 1859-1933\" (PDF). ''British Birds''. Retrieved 1 April 2020.</ref> \n\n=== Work ===\nOn May 4, 1892, '''Claudia Hartert''' and her husband left [[Le Havre|Le Havre, France]] for an extended trip to the [[West Indies]] in the [[Caribbean Sea]]. On May 19 they reached the [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|island of Saint Thomas]], where Claudia saw her first hummingbird, the Blue Star Antilles hummingbird.\n\nTogether with her husband she was the first to describe the blue-tailed Buffon hummingbird subspecies (''Chalybura buffonii intermedia'' Hartert, E & Hartert, C, 1894). \u00a0The article ''On a collection of Humming Birds from Ecuador and Mexico'' appears to be their only joint publication. In ''Feathered World'' she published many observations from her trip to the West Indies in addition to many illustrations.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/54374|title=Die Gefiederte Welt.|date=1893|publisher=VFV Verbands- und Fachschriftenverlag GmbH & Co. [etc.]|volume=jahrg. 22 (1893)|location=Wiesbaden [etc.] :}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1882, the Hartert couple moved to [[Tring|Tring, England]], to work with [[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild]], becoming the long time director of the [[Natural History Museum at Tring]], which at the time was privately owned by Rothschild.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2_BKAAAAYAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Claudia+Hartert&q=Claudia+Hartert&hl=en|title=Tier und Museum|date=1988|publisher=Gesellschaft der Freunde und F\u00f6rderer des Museums Alexander Koenig|language=de}}</ref> Claudia managed the museum's library for at least a few years. The couple lived a normal life there despite their dual allegiances to Germany and England until the beginnings of [[World War I]]. While in Tring, Claudia's husband became a naturalized English citizen, according to an excerpt<ref name=\":5\" /> of a May 1915 letter from Claudia Hartert in Tring to Mrs. Noerdlinger, wife of Eugene Robert Noerdlinger, \"German suspect, resident in Jersey.\" <blockquote>\"We have now been 24 years in England. How English people have gone down in my esteem. I am too much of a German to be able to think otherwise. My young son was at Oxford when he had to become a soldier, thank God he is still in our neighborhood.... My husband it is true has been naturalized for 13 years, or more, but is not a born native.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://richardshepherd.net/2006/ClaudiasSunangel.html|title=Claudia's sunangel|website=richardshepherd.net|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Illustrations ===\nClaudia Hartert was acknowledged as an excellent illustrator,<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/novitateszoologi08lond|title=Novitates Zoologicae|date=1901|publisher=London|others=London Natural History Museum Library}}</ref> and provided 493 illustrations that appeared in ''A practical handbook of British birds.'' Her figures went without attribution in the first edition that was printed before World War I.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Witherby|first=H. F.|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/53495|title=A practical handbook of British birds,|publisher=Witherby,|volume=v. 1; pt. 1-8|location=London,}}</ref> In the preface to the second volume [[Harry Forbes Witherby]] wrote: <blockquote>\"I have also to acknowledge my gratitude to Mrs. Hartert for the care and trouble she has taken over the text figures, almost all of which have been drawn by her from specimens in the Tring Museum.\"</blockquote>Some of the drawings also appear in the five-volume ''[[Handbook of British Birds|The Handbook of British Birds]]'', that Witherby published in 1952.  \n\n=== Later years ===\nClaudia Hartert retained her English citizenship after moving to Berlin in 1930.<ref name=\":5\" /> Her husband died there in 1933.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nin 1939, due to political difficulties, and with the help of British ornithologist [[Phyllis Barclay-Smith]], she moved from Berlin to the St. Willebrodus nursing home in [[Wassenaar|Wassenaar, Netherlands]]. On August 21, 1940, Hartert moved to the St. Carolus nursing home in [[Hilversum|Hilversum, Netherlands]], where she lived until her death 24 August 1958, at 95 years of age.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Dedication names ==\n\n* John David Digues La Touche in 1922 named the claudialist (''Phylloscopus claudiae'' (La Touche, 1922)) after Mrs. Hartert.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Beolens|first=Bo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g_3QDwAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA122&dq=Claudia+Hartert&hl=en|title=The Eponym Dictionary of Birds|last2=Watkins|first2=Michael|last3=Grayson|first3=Michael|date=2020-03-19|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-4729-8269-8|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Heliangelus claudia'' Hartert, E , 1895 is today considered a synonym for the Longuemare sun nymph (''Heliangelus clarisse'' (Longuemare, 1841)).<ref name=\":3\" />\n* The genus Claudia Hartert, E, 1896  is today a synonym for ''Tachornis Gosse'', 1847.    (Hartert himself corrected the name in 1916 after advice from Charles Chubb (1851\u20131924) and Tom Iredale (1880\u20131972) with ''Reinarda'', because the name Claudia St\u00e5l,1865 had already been assigned.)\n\n== Selected publications ==\n\n*Ernst Hartert, Claudia Hartert: ''On a collection of Humming Birds from Ecuador and Mexico''. In: Novitates zoologicae: A journal of zoology in connection with the Tring Museum. Volume\u00a01, 1894, pp.\u00a043-64<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://species.wikimedia.org/wiki/Claudia_Bernadine_Elisabeth_Hartert|title=Claudia Bernadine Elisabeth Hartert - Wikispecies|website=species.wikimedia.org|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n* Illustration in: The feathered world . Volume\u00a0 12 , No.\u00a08, February 23, 1893, pp.\u00a071-72 https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/54374#page/83/mode/1up<ref name=\":0\" />\n* The same illustration appeared in The feathered world . Volume\u00a0 12 , No.\u00a09 , March 2, 1893, pp.\u00a081-82 https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/54374#page/103/mode/1up<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/54374|title=Die Gefiederte Welt.|date=1893|publisher=VFV Verbands- und Fachschriftenverlag GmbH & Co. [etc.]|volume=jahrg. 22 (1893)|location=Wiesbaden [etc.] :}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FZtIAQAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA91&dq=Claudia+Hartert&hl=en|title=Die Gefiederte Welt|date=1893|publisher=VFV Verbands- und Fachschriftenverlag GmbH & Company|language=de}}</ref>\n* The same illustration appeared in: The feathered world. Volume\u00a0 12 , No.\u00a010, March 9, 1893, pp.\u00a091-95\n* Hartert, Claudia B. E. ''[pen and Ink Drawings of Palearctic Birds]''. 1900. Print.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hartert|first=Claudia Bernadine Elisabeth|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/pen-and-ink-drawings-of-palearctic-birds/oclc/182907358&referer=brief_results|title=Pen and ink drawings of Palearctic birds|date=1900|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=worldcat.org|pages=|language=German|oclc=182907358}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hartert, Claudia}}\n\n\n[[Category:British ornithologists]]\n[[Category:Women ornithologists]]\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:British women artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century women artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Userspace draft|source=ArticleWizard|date=April 2020}} \n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Claudia Bernadine Elisabeth Hartert\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Claudia Endris\n| birth_date         = 21 June 1863\n| birth_place        = [[Coesfeld]], Germany\n| death_date         = 24 August 1958\n| burial_place       = \n| death_place        = [[Hilversum|Hilversum, Netherlands]]\n| othername          = \n| occupation         = Ornithologist, illustrator\n| years_active       = \n| spouse             = [[Ernst Hartert]] (m. July 1891)\n| signature          = \n| children           = Joachim Karl Hartert (1893\u20131916)\n| mother             = Alwine Florentine Sophie B\u00f6cker\n| father             = Lieutenant Colonel Joachim Endris\n| nationality        = British\n}}\n'''Claudia Bernadine Elisabeth Hartert,''' (1863 \u2013 1958) was a British/German ornithologist and illustrator. She was a British citizen born in Germany. \n\n== Biography ==\nBorn '''Claudia Endris'''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://nha.blob.core.windows.net/scans/BS%20Overlijden/Hilversum/1958/NL_HlmNHA_O_HIL_1958_0308.jpg|title=Scan of Death Certificate|last=Endris|first=Claudia Bernadine Elizabeth|date=1958|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=simpleSearch&cqlMode=true&query=nid=115349731X|title=Katalog der Deutschen Nationalbibliothek|website=portal.dnb.de|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> (or Endriss) (21 June 1863 in [[Coesfeld]], Germany),<ref name=\":1\" /> Claudia's father was Lieutenant Colonel Joachim Endris, her mother's name was Alwine Florentine Sophie, n\u00e9e B\u00f6cker.<ref name=\":1\" /> Claudia's older brother was Gustav Joachim (b. 1862). \n\nIn July 1891, Claudia married the ornithologist [[Ernst Hartert]]<ref name=\":2\" /> in [[Frankfurt|Frankfurt am Main]], Germany, with whom she had a son named son Joachim Karl Hartert, (1893\u20131916), who was killed as an English soldier during the [[Battle of the Somme]] in [[France]].<ref name=\":4\">\"Obituary: ERNST JOHANN OTTO HARTERT. 1859-1933\" (PDF). ''British Birds''. Retrieved 1 April 2020.</ref> \n\n=== Work ===\nOn May 4, 1892, '''Claudia Hartert''' and her husband left [[Le Havre|Le Havre, France]] for an extended trip to the [[West Indies]] in the [[Caribbean Sea]]. On May 19 they reached the [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|island of Saint Thomas]], where Claudia saw her first hummingbird, the Blue Star Antilles hummingbird.\n\nTogether with her husband she was the first to describe the blue-tailed Buffon hummingbird subspecies (''Chalybura buffonii intermedia'' Hartert, E & Hartert, C, 1894). \u00a0The article ''On a collection of Humming Birds from Ecuador and Mexico'' appears to be their only joint publication. In ''Feathered World'' she published many observations from her trip to the West Indies in addition to many illustrations.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/54374|title=Die Gefiederte Welt.|date=1893|publisher=VFV Verbands- und Fachschriftenverlag GmbH & Co. [etc.]|volume=jahrg. 22 (1893)|location=Wiesbaden [etc.] :}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1882, the Hartert couple moved to [[Tring|Tring, England]], to work with [[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild]], becoming the long time director of the [[Natural History Museum at Tring]], which at the time was privately owned by Rothschild.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2_BKAAAAYAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Claudia+Hartert&q=Claudia+Hartert&hl=en|title=Tier und Museum|date=1988|publisher=Gesellschaft der Freunde und F\u00f6rderer des Museums Alexander Koenig|language=de}}</ref> Claudia managed the museum's library for at least a few years. The couple lived a normal life there despite their dual allegiances to Germany and England until the beginnings of [[World War I]]. While in Tring, Claudia's husband became a naturalized English citizen, according to an excerpt<ref name=\":5\" /> of a May 1915 letter from Claudia Hartert in Tring to Mrs. Noerdlinger, wife of Eugene Robert Noerdlinger, \"German suspect, resident in Jersey.\" <blockquote>\"We have now been 24 years in England. How English people have gone down in my esteem. I am too much of a German to be able to think otherwise. My young son was at Oxford when he had to become a soldier, thank God he is still in our neighborhood.... My husband it is true has been naturalized for 13 years, or more, but is not a born native.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://richardshepherd.net/2006/ClaudiasSunangel.html|title=Claudia's sunangel|website=richardshepherd.net|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Illustrations ===\nClaudia Hartert was acknowledged as an excellent illustrator,<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/novitateszoologi08lond|title=Novitates Zoologicae|date=1901|publisher=London|others=London Natural History Museum Library}}</ref> and provided 493 illustrations that appeared in ''A practical handbook of British birds.'' Her figures went without attribution in the first edition that was printed before World War I.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Witherby|first=H. F.|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/53495|title=A practical handbook of British birds,|publisher=Witherby,|volume=v. 1; pt. 1-8|location=London,}}</ref> In the preface to the second volume [[Harry Forbes Witherby]] wrote: <blockquote>\"I have also to acknowledge my gratitude to Mrs. Hartert for the care and trouble she has taken over the text figures, almost all of which have been drawn by her from specimens in the Tring Museum.\"</blockquote>Some of the drawings also appear in the five-volume ''[[Handbook of British Birds|The Handbook of British Birds]]'', that Witherby published in 1952.  \n\n=== Later years ===\nClaudia Hartert retained her English citizenship after moving to Berlin in 1930.<ref name=\":5\" /> Her husband died there in 1933.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nin 1939, due to political difficulties, and with the help of British ornithologist [[Phyllis Barclay-Smith]], she moved from Berlin to the St. Willebrodus nursing home in [[Wassenaar|Wassenaar, Netherlands]]. On August 21, 1940, Hartert moved to the St. Carolus nursing home in [[Hilversum|Hilversum, Netherlands]], where she lived until her death 24 August 1958, at 95 years of age.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Dedication names ==\n\n* John David Digues La Touche in 1922 named the claudialist (''Phylloscopus claudiae'' (La Touche, 1922)) after Mrs. Hartert.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Beolens|first=Bo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g_3QDwAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA122&dq=Claudia+Hartert&hl=en|title=The Eponym Dictionary of Birds|last2=Watkins|first2=Michael|last3=Grayson|first3=Michael|date=2020-03-19|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-4729-8269-8|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Heliangelus claudia'' Hartert, E , 1895 is today considered a synonym for the Longuemare sun nymph (''Heliangelus clarisse'' (Longuemare, 1841)).<ref name=\":3\" />\n* The genus Claudia Hartert, E, 1896  is today a synonym for ''Tachornis Gosse'', 1847.    (Hartert himself corrected the name in 1916 after advice from Charles Chubb (1851\u20131924) and Tom Iredale (1880\u20131972) with ''Reinarda'', because the name Claudia St\u00e5l,1865 had already been assigned.)\n\n== Selected publications ==\n\n*Ernst Hartert, Claudia Hartert: ''On a collection of Humming Birds from Ecuador and Mexico''. In: Novitates zoologicae: A journal of zoology in connection with the Tring Museum. Volume\u00a01, 1894, pp.\u00a043-64<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://species.wikimedia.org/wiki/Claudia_Bernadine_Elisabeth_Hartert|title=Claudia Bernadine Elisabeth Hartert - Wikispecies|website=species.wikimedia.org|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n* Illustration in: The feathered world . Volume\u00a0 12 , No.\u00a08, February 23, 1893, pp.\u00a071-72 https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/54374#page/83/mode/1up<ref name=\":0\" />\n* The same illustration appeared in The feathered world . Volume\u00a0 12 , No.\u00a09 , March 2, 1893, pp.\u00a081-82 https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/54374#page/103/mode/1up<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/54374|title=Die Gefiederte Welt.|date=1893|publisher=VFV Verbands- und Fachschriftenverlag GmbH & Co. [etc.]|volume=jahrg. 22 (1893)|location=Wiesbaden [etc.] :}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FZtIAQAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA91&dq=Claudia+Hartert&hl=en|title=Die Gefiederte Welt|date=1893|publisher=VFV Verbands- und Fachschriftenverlag GmbH & Company|language=de}}</ref>\n* The same illustration appeared in: The feathered world. Volume\u00a0 12 , No.\u00a010, March 9, 1893, pp.\u00a091-95\n* Hartert, Claudia B. E. ''[pen and Ink Drawings of Palearctic Birds]''. 1900. Print.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hartert|first=Claudia Bernadine Elisabeth|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/pen-and-ink-drawings-of-palearctic-birds/oclc/182907358&referer=brief_results|title=Pen and ink drawings of Palearctic birds|date=1900|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=worldcat.org|pages=|language=German|oclc=182907358}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hartert, Claudia}}\n\n\n[[:Category:British ornithologists]]\n[[:Category:Women ornithologists]]\n[[:Category:1863 births]]\n[[:Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[:Category:British women artists]]\n[[:Category:20th-century artists]]\n[[:Category:20th-century women artists]]\n[[:Category:20th-century British women artists]]\n", "name_user": "AMM Pittsburgh", "label": "safe", "comment": "added categories", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claudia_Bernadine_Elisabeth_Hartert"}
